The praetor then awarded to one of the claimants possession of the thing pending the suit, and made him bind himself with sureties to his adversary to restore both the subject of dispute and the mesne profits or value of the interim possession, in the event of losing the cause. Both parties gave pledges to the praetor for the penal sum which the loser was to forfeit. The wand or straw which they wielded represented a lance, the symbol of absolute dominion, for the best title to property was held to be conquest. Accordingly the law of property is administered in the Centumviral court at the present day under the symbol of a lance.

ξ 17. If the subject of dispute was such as could not conveniently be carried or led before the praetor, a portion was brought into court, and the formalities were enacted over it as if it was the whole. If it was a flock of sheep or herd of goats, a single sheep or goat, or a single tuft of hair was brought ; if it was a ship or column, a fragment was broken off and brought; if it was laud, a clod 3 if it was a house, a tile 3 if it was an inheritance. . . .
